std::expected
flatmap
std::print

mordern cpp
Genuine opportunities
1. std::expected in the parser — this is the biggest one
ParseResult has a success bool + errors vector — that's exactly what std::expected was designed to replace.
 The individual handlers like parse_positive_size could return std::expected<size_t, std::string> 
 instead of returning 0 and side-effecting into an error list. 
 Cleaner call sites, no implicit sentinel values.


3. std::print / std::println in view.cpp
You're already using std::format — C++23 std::print is the natural next step. Eliminates the std::cout << std::format(...) pattern entirely.

4. Ranges pipelines in analyzer.cpp
compute_recent_files, compute_symlinks, compute_empty_directories are all filter → sort → return operations on vectors. These map directly to std::ranges::filter_view pipelines. compute_largest_N_files uses std::partial_sort_copy which could become a ranges partial sort. These are already the kind of thing you'd write with ranges naturally.

5. std::flat_map for extension stats
compute_extension_stats builds an unordered_map then sorts at the end. Since you always end up with a sorted output, std::flat_map (C++23) — which is a sorted, contiguous key-value structure — fits better and has better cache behaviour.

Summary
Feature	Where	Value
std::expected	parser	High — replaces error-flag + side-effects pattern
Concepts	deque, scheduler	Medium — cleaner than static_assert
std::print	view	Low effort, natural upgrade
Ranges pipelines	analyzer	Medium — cleaner filter/sort chains
std::flat_map	analyzer extension stats	Low-medium — cache win, fits the usage
The parser std::expected refactor is the one I'd do first — it changes the design in a meaningful way. The rest are refinements.





unning actions in parallel — yes, this is real
Looking at main.cpp:43-46:


for (const auto& action : result.actions)
    std::visit(executor, action);
Actions run sequentially. But compute_extension_stats, compute_recent_files, and compute_largest_N_Files are completely independent — they only read tree. If a user runs --extensions --recent 7d --largest-files 10, that's three full O(N) passes over all files done one after another.

These could be launched with std::async in parallel, results collected into a vector in submission order, then printed sequentially. The Executor's cached state (file_stats, metrics, empty_dirs) would need to be pre-warmed before spawning, since those use mutable optional which isn't thread-safe. But the heavy compute functions themselves only take const DirectoryTree& — safe to run concurrently.

That's the most interesting remaining optimization and it's cross-platform.

